Research Experience
Motion states of stable droplets actuated by a piezoelectric nozzle
2018.06-Present
Advisor: Prof. Haisheng Fang, Multiscale Process Modeling Lab (MPML), HUST
Background: Piezoelectric inkjet printing is a technology widely used in mechanical, electronic and biomedical industries. Most
studies have focused on the acoustic characteristics of the pressure channel or the jet stability, but little attention has been paid to
the motion state of a single droplet, which have a great effect on the printing accuracy.
My work:
● Enhanced the performance of the inkjet Micro-dispensing Platform, and carried out systematic experiments to capture images
of the single droplet at different operating conditions by CCD camera
● Used level set method to simulate drop formation and oscillation during moving to get characteristics of its motion state
● Wrote MATLAB codes as a post-processing tool to process pictures and data obtained in experiments
● Analyzed and interpreted the experimental and simulated results using the dimensional analysis method
● Independently prepared a paper for an academic journal based on the above study as the first author
Co-firing sludge in a pulverized coal-fired utility boiler
：
Influence of secondary air (SA) distribution
2018.04-Present
Advisor: Associate Prof. Qingyan Fang, the State Key Laboratory of Coal Combustion (SKLCC), HUST
Background: Incineration is an efficient method to achieve thorough, innocuous and economical sludge disposal. However
considering the unique characteristics of sludge with high nitrogen, volatile and moisture content, it is vital to investigate how the
aerodynamic field and oxygen-feed in the boiler should be modified to maximize the efficiency and minimize the pollutants
emission.
My work:
● Designed two sets of computational conditions to comprehensively study the influence of secondary air distribution on sludge
co-combustion
● Used ANSYS Fluent to simulate combustion in a full-scale 100 MW boiler model and analyzed the resulting temperature
profiles, heat flux, coal burnout rate, CO and NO
x
emission
● Proposed an optimal SA distribution taking into account both the boiler efficiency and environmental effects
● Independently prepared a paper for an academic journal as the first author
High throughput spray coating of membranes for applications in desalination and waste chemical recovery
2017.07-2017.08
Advisor: Associate Prof. David B. Go, Associate Prof. William Phillip, Department of Aerospace and Mechanical engineering,
University of Notre Dame
Background: The efficient separation of metal ions from aqueous solution is important for public health and the environment. To
achieve this, electrospray is a promising method to realize high throughput spray coating of nanostructured membranes which can
absorb ions selectively. However, to optimize the manufacturing process, various working conditions and the solution chemistry

My work:
● Assisted in rebuilding the piezoelectric-based spray system
● Conducted spray experiments on a traditional electrospray system by varying spray rate and duration
● Conducted piezoelectric-based spray experiments by varying spray duration and solvent (DMSO &MEK) make-up
● Characterized the hydraulic permeability and copper-capture ability of membranes by a circular hole punch and UV-Vis
